Good afternoon Rishav, my name is Matt, I am assisting Sean with collecting gap documents and gap inquiries while he is away on vacation. I will attempt to explain this question to the best of my capacity for you, but for any further more in depth questions, you will need to wait until Sean returns and speak to him directly. 
To explain further about your question regarding the Adjusted Cash Value and the Canadian Black Book value, in your contract, it states that the insurer has the right to verify that the amount that the insurance company paid to you on the settlement cheque is accurate and appropriate given many factors regarding your vehicle. This could be but is not limited to, km's on the vehicle at time of loss, age of vehicle, etc. In this case, we checked the Canadian Black Book Value for your vehicle, and the amount given to you by your insurance company was less than the suggested retail value of the vehicle according to Canadian Black Book. 

This being said, our insurer exercised their right (as per your contract) to use the value given by Canadian Black Book during the gap payout calculation, and this is why you are not receiving reimbursement for the whole difference between your outstanding loan amount and the amount given to you by your insurance company on the settlement cheque.
If you would like to dispute this matter, please speak with your insurance company in regards to how they calculated your settlement payout total. 
Best regards, 
Matthew Puls
